##Preparation of the Data
import numpy as np
def vectorize_sequences(sequences, dimension=10000):
    results = np.zeros((len(sequences), dimension))
    for i, sequence in enumerate(sequences):
        for j in sequence:
            results[i, j] = 1.
    return results

#Building the model using relu and compiling it
#Our input data is simply vectors, and our labels are scalars (1s and 0s): this is the simplest configuration you'll ever see. A basic stack of fully-connected (Dense) layers with relu activations is one sort of network that works well on such a job. Dense(16, activation='relu').
#Finally, select a loss function and an optimizer. Because we are dealing with a binary classification problem and our network's output is a probability (we finish with a single-unit layer with sigmoid activation), we should apply the binary_crossentropy loss.

from tensorflow import keras
from tensorflow.keras import layers

model = keras.Sequential([
    layers.Dense(16, activation="relu"),
    layers.Dense(16, activation="relu"),
    layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")
])

#summary
We created a baseline neural network model with a single hidden layer of 16 units after importing the data and adjusting the word count and review scope parameters. This layers activation function was set to relu, and binary_crossentropy was selected as the loss function. We explored with many approaches to improve model interpretation. Models with one and three hidden layers were compared first, as we changed the number of hidden layers. Nevertheless, it became clear from training and testing on training and test datasets that the model with three hidden layers outperformed the single hidden layer model in accuracy and test sensitivity by a very small margin.

We next examined the effects of changing the number of hidden units in the layers—32 and 64 units, to be precise. We discovered that adding more hidden units often led to higher test sensitivity and accuracy by training and testing models with different numbers of hidden units. But more than one unit may cause overfitting, it was mentioned. We also examined the impact of substituting the binary_crossentropy loss function with the mean squared error (mse) loss function. We discovered that the inclusion of mse loss did not substantially change the interpretation of the model after training and assessing it and comparing the outcomes to the baseline model.

#conclusion
Neural network models with different configurations showed different patterns of sensitivity and loss. Among these, the Model_Hyper with its three densely packed layers, showed the lowest loss and the highest delicacy. This result implies that this specific arrangement is best suited for IMDB dataset interpretation. Moreover, using the mean squared error (MSE) loss function produced the least amount of loss, whereas the tanh activation function resulted in less delicacy because of problems with vanishing gradients. Regularization approaches, showed promise in decreasing overfitting, and the Adam optimizer proved to be beneficial.To address any overfitting concerns, we implemented dropout regularization in the trials last phase. We saw a significant improvement in confirmation delicacy compared to the baseline model by integrating dropout layers into a new model and performing training and assessment on both the training and test datasets. To be more precise, the use of dropout regularization improved model performance, reducing concerns about overfitting and improving accuracy.
Overall, the performance of the models was much enhanced by the addition of dropout regularization, with Model hyper being the model that performed the best out of all the models that were assessed. Dropout regularization is an efficient way to improve the neural networks interpretive power, as demonstrated by the thorough analysis that took into account changes in sensitivity, loss, and the effects of various configurations.
